{"id":"1305.1250","submitter":"Xiaolin Yang","authors":"Xiaolin Yang and Jiancheng Wang","title":"YNOGK: A new public code for calculating null geodesics in the Kerr\n  spacetime","comments":"Accepted for publication in ApJS, 58 pages, 17 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/0067-0049/207/1/6","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.HE gr-qc","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Following \\cite{dexagol2009} we present a new public code for the fast\ncalculation of null geodesics in the Kerr spacetime. Using Weierstrass' and\nJacobi's elliptic functions, we express all coordinates and affine parameters\nas analytical and numerical functions of a parameter $p$, which is an integral\nvalue along the geodesic. This is a main difference of our code compares with\nprevious similar ones. The advantage of this treatment is that the information\nabout the turning points do not need to be specified in advance by the user,\nand many applications such as imaging, the calculation of line profiles or the\nobserver-emitter problem, etc become root finding problems. All elliptic\nintegrations are computed by Carlson's elliptic integral method as\n\\cite{dexagol2009} did, which guarantees the fast computational speed of our\ncode. The formulae to compute the constants of motion given by\n\\cite{cunnbard1973} have been extended, which allow one readily to handle the\nsituations, in which the emitter or the observer has arbitrary distance and\nmotion state with respect to the central compact object. The validation of the\ncode has been extensively tested by its application to toy problems from the\nliterature. The source FORTRAN code is freely available for download on the\nweb.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 6 May 2013 17:21:23 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-15"}
